<section class="py-20 px-8 md:px-20 bg-navy">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
    <h2 class="text-4xl font-serif font-semibold text-ivory mb-4">What Euler Started</h2>
    <p class="text-ivory-dim text-lg italic mb-10">
      The abstraction became a discipline. The discipline became infrastructure.
    </p>

    <p class="text-lg text-ivory/90 leading-relaxed mb-6">
      Graph theory as a field took shape over the next two centuries: quiet,
      academic, and largely unnoticed. Gustav Kirchhoff used graphs to analyse
      electrical circuits in 1845. Arthur Cayley used them to count chemical
      isomers in 1857. In 1936, the Hungarian mathematician
      <strong class="text-amber">Dénes König</strong> wrote the first textbook
      devoted to the subject, eight years before the Allies landed at Normandy,
      and two decades before the algorithms that would make graphs indispensable.
    </p>

    <p class="text-lg text-ivory/90 leading-relaxed mb-6">
      Then the applications arrived all at once. The Cold War motivated
      network-flow theory at RAND. The internet turned every packet into
      a graph-routing problem. Web search turned every page into a node in
      a graph with billions of edges. Today, the abstraction Euler invented
      to dismiss a parlour puzzle is the mathematical substrate of modern
      infrastructure. You have used it every time you have opened a web browser.
    </p>

